==Chinese==

===Glyph origin 1===
{{Han etym}}
Two kinds of glyph are found in Warring States era:

;The glyph in Sanjin ({{lang|zh|三晉}})
A compound of {{lang|zh|[[犬]]}} at left + {{lang|zh|[[羊]]}} at right.
* Dog and sheep are seen to bring luck ([[#Chineserefs|Zhao, 1999]]).
* {{l|och|羊}} is phonetic ([[#Chineserefs|Liu, 2022]]). 

; The glyph in Chu ({{lang|zh|楚}})
A compound of upside-down {{lang|zh|[[矢]]}} at left + {{lang|zh|[[犬]]}} at right, with unknown intention ([[#Chineserefs|Chen, 2005]]).

Qin-Han dynasty era inherited the Sanjin glyph with {{lang|zh|[[犬]]}} at top and {{lang|zh|[[羊]]}} at bottom ([[#Chineserefs|Liu, 2022]]). This is the source of the contemporary {{lang|zh|幸}} ([[#Chineserefs|Chen, 2015]]).

''{{w|Shuo Wen}}'' interpreted it as a compound of {{Han compound|屰|夭|t1=opposite|t2=death|nocap=yes}} – lucky to be alive; fortunate.

